":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swete","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset): from the Middle English personal name <i>Swet(e)</i> (Old English <i>Swēt(a)</i> (male), <i>Swēte</i> (female)), or else a nickname from Middle English <i>swet(e)</i>, <i>sweyt</i> ‘sweet; pleasing; beloved; attractive’ (Old English <i>swēte</i>, <i>swōt</i>), from which the personal names derive. Compare   Swett  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Suess   and French   Ledoux   ‘the gentle, the sweet’."],"variants":[{"name":"Sweeting","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Sweting</i> (Old English <i>Swēting</i>, a derivative of <i>swēte</i> ‘sweet’; see   Sweet  ).","nickname from Middle English <i>sweting</i> ‘darling, sweetheart’, used for a popular and attractive person, or for someone who habitually addressed people with the term."]},{"name":"Swett","meanings":["Altered form of English   Sweet  . This surname is also found in Chile, where it is at least in part of North American origin.","Americanized (possibly shortened) form of an unidentified eastern Ashkenazic surname.","Americanized form of Polish   Szwed  ."]},{"name":"Sott","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>sot</i>, Old English <i>sott</i> ‘foolish’, also commonly used as a noun denoting a foolish person.","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>sot(e)</i>, <i>swot(e)</i>, Old English <i>swōt</i> ‘sweet, pleasant, beloved’, also used as a noun meaning ‘dear one’. Compare   Sweet  .","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English and Old English <i>sōt</i>, Old Norse <i>sót</i> ‘soot’, also used as an adjective ‘sooty’, perhaps given to someone with black hair. Among the Scandinavians it was used as a personal name, <i>Sóti</i>, which was brought to England by the Vikings."]},{"name":"Sweat","meanings":["English: variant of   Sweet  ."]},{"name":"Sweatt","meanings":["English: variant of   Sweet  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":64,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Knight Of Caston John Swete was born on 9 January 1390, in Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Caston Swete Sr, was 20 and his mother, Sarah Alice Peterson, was 20. He married Alice Sweet in Wymondham, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 10 January 1475, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 85."},"et":{"9 January 1390–10 January 1475":"9. jaanuar 1390–10. jaanuar 1475","1390–1475":"1390–1475","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1425–1487":"1425–1487","1371–1431":"1371–1431","1370–1475":"1370–1475","9 January 1390":"9. jaanuar 1390","1425":"1425","10 January 1475":"10. jaanuar 1475","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1475":"1475","1431":"1431","1395":"1395","about 1431":"umbes 1431","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","South Milton, Devon